{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-00505/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-00505"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:05:05"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["medium shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["high"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["fixed"]}},{"label":{"none":["Lighting"]},"value":{"none":["low key"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["three shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A man and woman pour tea while another woman watches."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-00505","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-00505"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/canvas/1/d8a0f369-e663-44b6-81d9-045390268025","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T15:37:39.007Z","creator":"Clara Smith","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Reynolds and Cyril pour their tea as Johanna watches on. At this point, a first-time viewer has no clue who Cyril is, likely taking her to be a partner, and won’t learn what exactly her relationship to Reynolds really is until further in the film. Nonetheless, the way the siblings synchronize as they prepare their tea clearly demonstrates how intertwined they are. PTA leaves these details unstated and thus forces viewers to share in the confusion that Alma will feel when she is thrust into Reynolds’s life.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:757.203947368421,421.5021929824562,348.6074561403509,272.88377192982443"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/canvas/1/e7a7e9a0-1512-425b-b6da-90a44da2420d","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T15:38:07.743Z","creator":"Clara Smith","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>In an <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW52232058 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.setdecorators.org/?art=film_decor_features&amp;SHOW=SetDecor_Film_Phantom_Thread\"><u>interview</u></a>, set designer Véronique Melery describes the care and thought put into dressing Reynolds’s dining room with elements both foreign and domestic—“contrasts between the traditional image of the perfect aristocratic, as in silver English breakfast utensils, and the audacious choices of an artist touched by the qualities of authentic craftsmanship” (Berg, “Set Decor”).&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00505/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:1039.7039473684208,789.8464912280701,378.4320175438595,212.53289473684208"}}}]}]}]}